HT|b|cs|1|cp|4|fp||at|
^-{ The Case Against New Minor Forcing }
^-|cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|The problems with New Minor Forcing bid stem from the ambiguity of the bid. Sometimes responder has an invitational hand. Other times he has enough to force to game. Next I like to illustrate a few of them.|
PG| ***** 1 ***** |


NT||

qx|a,hide|ST||pn|Opener,,Responder.|MD|1skqhj65dkq5cq7642,,,|rh||AH|Marty Bergen Online Lesson|AH|2 Way Checkback|AH|Board 1|MB|1cp1sp1np|NT|^B@2
No problem. Responder has 5 spades and interest in a spade game or possibly a NT and if opener has a maximum. So he bids 2@D as New Minor Forcing.|MB|2dp|
PG| ***** 2 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Opener has no major and does not have a maximum. So he bids 2NT. Responder, only holding an invitational hand, passes.|MB|2nppp|md|0,0,saj932h4daj87cj53,0|
PG| ***** 3 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Yuck! This is not a good contract. On an opening heart lead, the defense will take at least 5 heart tricks and 2 club tricks. 2NT is down at least 2.|
PG| ***** 4 ***** |


NT||
cp|8|AT|
^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|After responder bid the new minor (2@D in this case), opener's first priority is to show length in a major when he has it. With 3 spades or 4 hearts, he will bid his major. With neither major he bids NT. |
PG| ***** 5 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Usually he bids 2NT, but with a maximum he will jump to 3NT. And he needs to jump to 3NT with the right hand because he does not want to languish in a part score when responder only has an invitational hand.|
PG| ***** 6 ***** |


NT||
%%%
qx|a,hide|ST||pn|Opener,,Responder.|MD|1skqjhqjdjt9ca8432,,sa63hakt93d6ckt65,|rh||AH|Marty Bergen Online Lesson|AH|2 Way Checkback|AH|Board 2|MB|1cp1hp1np|NT|^B@2
Look what happens on this hand. The auction starts 1@C-1@H-1NT, a routine auction. This time responder has a very nice hand, definitely enough for game. With his club fit and singleton, a slam is possible. He certainly likes having his 14 HCP in aces and kings.|
PG| ***** 7 ***** |


NT|^B@2
So again responder bids 2@D as New Minor Forcing.|MB|2d|
PG| ***** 8 ***** |


AT| Opener has 14 HCP, a 5-card suit, and 2 upgradeable honors in responder's suit. So he has a clear maximum and jumps to 3NT. He can't risk responder passing 2NT. I think most good players would pass 3NT with responder's hand. That is what I would do. |mb|p3nppp|
PG| ***** 9 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Yes, you might belong in clubs or hearts, but you really don't want to introduce another suit at the 4-level. Not to mention there are some players who would treat a 4@C bid by responder as Gerber.|
PG| ***** 10 ***** |


NT|^B@2
On a diamond lead, a suit in which the opponents have length and strength, 3NT is going down real fast. Meanwhile 4@H, 5@C, and even 6@C are all reasonable contracts.|
PG| ***** 11 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|In summary, here is New Minor Forcing reality. Because New Minor Forcing is not forcing to game, it is a "maybe" situation. Responder does not promise a rebid. This means opener must jump with a maximum. This often gets in responder's way as we saw in Hand 2.|
PG| ***** 12 ***** |


NT||AT|
^B@2^*BMovie Maker: Marty has more samples or as he calls it, "my New Minor Forcing rant" but I am not allowed to deliver all of them here. You know the way -:).^*N|
PG| ***** 13 ***** |


NT||bt||
