qx|a,wide|HT|b|cs|1|cp|4|fp||at|
^-{ The Simple Structure For 2 Way Checkback }
^-|cp|8|AT|^b@2

^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|The beauty of 2 Way Checkback is that, after opener rebids 1NT, responder has 2 artificial rebids available.|
pg| ***** 17 ***** |


FP|2|at| 

Responder bids 2@C with an invitational hand
and 
bids 2@D to force to game.|FP||
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


AT|

There are 2 very distinct and specific paths responder can take. That is the key. Both players immediately know where the auction stands. Later on, no one has to wonder if partner's bid was or was not forcing. That is huge.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


AT|

2@C denies the strength to force to game. After 2@C we will sometimes get to game. However opener is more likely to have 12 HCP than 14 so much of the time we will stop in a part score. That is particularly true if we don't have an 8-card major suit fit.|
PG| ***** 20 ***** |


AT|

But when responder bids 2@D to force to game, the auction proceeds as if you had a 2 Over 1 Game Forcing auction. You have plenty of room to exchange information and decide which suit or NT to play in. You have no fear that you might be left in a part score. No one is ever forced to jump.|
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


AT|

If responder is sure he wants to play in 3NT or 4 of a major, he is welcome to jump there. But opener never jumps. In 2 Way Checkback auctions, opener's 1NT rebid says a lot about his strength and distribution. So it is much easier for both players to bid accurately.|
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||
%%%
qx|a,wide|AT|
^B@2^*BMM: ^*NIn the next several sections of his lesson, Marty explains the fine print and nuances of 2 Way Check back using seven examples. Then he follows with ^*BFYI^*N(s) before dealing with "Responder Bids 2@C Over 1NT." I wish I could bring then all to you, but then I would end up rooming in with the porcupines for good. -:). |
PG| ***** 23 ***** |


NT||
%%%
qx|a,wide|HT|b|cs|1|cp|4|fp||at|
^-{ Responder Bids 2@C Over 1NT }^-|cp|8|AT|^b@2

^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Our first topic discusses the auction when responder bids 2@C over opener's 1NT rebid. ^*NThis is an artificial bid denying the strength to force to game. It is one of the key bids in 2 Way Checkback.^*N|
PG| ***** 24 ***** |


AT| 

Over 2@C, opener ^*BMUST^*N bid 2@D. Period. Case closed. No exceptions. For the time being, responder is totally in charge.|
PG| ***** 25 ***** |


AT|

When responder has less than a game forcing hand, it is critical that he talk about his distribution immediately. Opener's 1NT rebid defined his hand type. But responder's first bid did not define his hand. That is one of the reasons that New Minor Forcing handles invitational hands so badly. |
PG| ***** 26 ***** |


AT|

By contrast, the 2@C bid is one of the best features of 2 Way Checkback. Until responder has said what he needs to, there is no chance that opener can get in responder's way. After responder has spoken, then and only then will opener resume being an active participant.|
PG| ***** 27 ***** |


AT| 

If responder wants to play in 2@D, he will pass opener's forced 2@D bid. This does not happen often. But it is one of the nice features of the convention. Responder can bid 2@C with a weak hand, positive that opener will bid 2@D. When responder has the right hand where 2@D is where he wants to play, he will go this route. |
PG| ***** 28 ***** |


NT||
%%%
qx|a,wide|HT|b|cs|1|cp|4|fp||at|
^-{ Responder Bids 2@C Over 1NT - Conti.}
^-|cp|8|AT|^b@2
^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|But the vast majority of the time, responder has an invitational hand. Responder will make a natural bid over 2@D. When he bids, he is saying he has exactly an invitational hand, nothing more and nothing less. He is describing his distribution, often announcing that he has a 5-card major. He only promised a 4-card major with his first bid. Whatever responder does, if he jumps (which is possible), it is not forcing. That is because responder chose to bid 2@C over 1NT rather than a game forcing 2@D. |
PG| ***** 29 ***** |


AT|

If opener chooses to bid over responder's invitational bid, that also is not forcing. Since the 2@C bid denied a game forcing hand, you will often stop in a part score. All bids, both suits and 2NT, are possible final contracts. |
PG| ***** 30 ***** |


AT|

This is very different from New Minor Forcing. Responder's new minor bid might be based on a game forcing hand or even a bigger hand. Both players must devote a great deal of energy trying to figure out 'Should I keep bidding or can I pass?' |
PG| ***** 31 ***** |


AT|

When responder holds an invitational hand, does he always have a 5-card major? The answer is no. But it is true that he most often has exactly 5 cards in his original major. With that hand, he will usually bid 2 of the major over 2@D. |
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


AT|

But other times responder could have a 4-card major or a 6-card major. One time that responder may have only 4 cards in his original major is when he passes 2@D. Then nobody cares how many cards he has in his major because the auction is over. More likely, when responder supports opener's minor, he will have a big fit for that suit and very possibly a side 4-card major. Next are some examples where it is right to bid 2@C over 1NT.|
PG| ***** 33 ***** |


NT||
%%
qx|5,wide|ST||pn|Opener,,Responder.|MD|1sjt8hajdaq9c87652,,s962hkqt94dkjt7cq,|rh||AH|Marty Bergen Online Lesson|AH|2 Way Checkback|AH|Hand 5|MB|1cP1hP1nP|cp|8|AT|
^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|The auction starts 1@C-1@H-1NT. Responder bids 2@C with a hand he evaluates as invitational because he really likes his quality red suits.|mb|2c|
PG| ***** 34 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Opener bids a forced 2@D, no thinking involved.|MB|p2dp|
PG| ***** 35 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Responder now bids 2@H to show 5 hearts. Opener thinks 'OK. I don't have a great hand. I don't have a heart fit. Let's bail out right here.'|mb|2h|
PG| ***** 36 ***** |


NT|^B@2
In the world of New Minor Forcing, responder would have to bid 2@D and opener would bid 2NT and play it there. Yikes! He is certainly losing at least 4 spade tricks and a lot of club tricks. The auction is so much better with 2 Way Checkback. The 2@C bid forces opener to rebid 2@D and ensures that he won't get in responder's way.|
PG| ***** 37 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Responder will get to talk about his 5-card major at the 2-level. Since responder has guaranteed only an invitational hand, opener can confidently pass without fear of missing a game or playing in a bad 2NT contract.|
PG| ***** 38 ***** |


NT||
%%
qx|a,wide|ST||pn|Opener,,Responder.|MD|1s64hakjd875caj652,,skqt97h7653daqc74,|rh||AH|Marty Bergen Online Lesson|AH|2 Way Checkback|AH|Hand 9|MB|1cp1sp1np|cp|8|AT|
^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Here the bidding starts with 1@C-P-1@S-P-1N-P.|
PG| ***** 39 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Responder's bids the artificial 2@C and Opener bids 2@D.|mb|2cp2dp|
PG| ***** 40 ***** |


AT| But, Responder bids 2@S.|MB|2sp|
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|What happened to responder's 2@H bid on this hand? I know responder does have 5 spades and 4 hearts. It could be right to play in hearts. But responder has 5 very chunky spades. Notice that even if opener had the singleton @SJ, this is a playable trump suit. As opposed to the hearts. That is not a suit I am particularly eager to play in.|
PG| ***** 42 ***** |


NT|^B@2
I know that length is more important than strength. But never forget that the strength of your long suits does matter, often greatly. In general, if you have a suit you don't want to play in, don't bid it. Responder is not interested in playing in hearts. |
PG| ***** 43 ***** |


NT||
%%
qx|a,wide|ST||pn|Opener,,Responder.|MD|1s64hakjd875caj652,,sa7532hq7643da4c4,|rh||AH|Marty Bergen Online Lesson|AH|2 Way Checkback|AH|Board 10|MB|1cP1sP1nP2cp2dp3hp4h|cp|8|AT|
^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|This time responder has a 5th heart. So after opener's forced 2@D bid, responder jumps to 3@H. This says responder is 5-5 in the majors. It is not forcing. It is invitational. That is what responder said when he bid 2@C over 1NT.|
PG| ***** 44 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Now opener thinks 'Oh! My partner has a 5th heart so we definitely have an 8-card heart fit. I love my 3 heart honors. I don't mind my 2 little spades although I would rather have some strength. Maybe I can get a ruff. And I have an ace on the side. I am happy to accept partner's invitation now that I am sure we have real heart fit.' So he bids 4@H. That is a sensible contract.|
PG| ***** 45 ***** |


NT||bt||
%%%
qx|a,hide|HT|b|cs|1|cp|4|fp||at|
^-{ Responder Bids 2@D Over 1NT}
^-|cp|8|AT|^b@2
^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|We are now ready for responder's 2@D rebid. When responder bids 2@D over 1NT, this artificial bid is forcing to game. Responder might have slam interest. But since game contracts occur far more often than slams, most of the time responder will be searching for the best game. As you will see later on in the lesson, there are some special bids set aside for slam tries that do not require that responder start with 2@D. But for now we will focus on the 2@D auctions which are more important for you to understand. (MM: We are not going to to report the slam tries.)|
PG| ***** 46 ***** |


AT|

Unless responder's first bid was 1@D, he usually has a 5-card major when he bids 2@D over 1NT. But, as with the 2@C response, it is possible that responder has a 4-card major or a 6-card major. With a 4-card major, opener almost always has good support for opener's minor.|
PG| ***** 47 ***** |


AT|

Over 2@D, opener gets to talk about his distribution. Since we know we are going to game, we have lots of room. So now we can allow opener to talk first. That is different than the 2@C auction. That is logical. Here we have time. With 2@C, responder needed to talk first.|
PG| ***** 48 ***** |


AT|

So in the first bid after 2@D, opener talks about his hand. Then responder gets his chance. Later on, both players will do the best they can, just like in a 2 over 1 auction. But unlike 2 over 1 auctions, because of the 1NT bid, opener has told a lot about his hand already. Therefore responder is the boss. But of course even the smartest boss sometimes needs information that only his subordinate can supply.|
PG| ***** 49 ***** |


AT|

We are now ready to discuss opener's rebid after 2@D. First of all, he must not jump. Period. |
PG| ***** 50 ***** |


NT||
%%%
qx|a,hide|HT|b|cs|1|cp|4|fp||at|
^-{ Opener's rebid After 2@D by Responder }
^-|cp|8|AT|^b@2
^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Regardless of which 2 bids were made prior to 1NT, opener's priorities are:|
PG| ***** 51 ***** |


fp|2|AT|

Priority ##1 is to show 3-card support for responder's major (if he bid one).|
PG| ***** 52 ***** |


AT|

Priority ##2 is to show 4-cards in an unbid major. Some players prefer to reverse those 2 priorities. That is OK. Do what you feel is best. It won't change the wonderful effect of the 2@D auctions. To me, since responder usually has a 5-card major, and I don't mind playing in a 5-3 fit rather than a 4-4 fit (although my students often feel differently), I like the first priority to show 3-card support.|
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


AT|

MM - Five other priorities rarely occur and I left them out of this mini-lesson to avoid confusing the reader.|
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^b@2^*BMarty Bergen: ^*N|cp||at|Don't lose sleep about memorizing the order. As you get more familiar with 2 Way Checkback, you will get a sense of what partner is expecting.|
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||
%%%
qx|a,hide|ST||pn|Opener,,Responder.|MD|1sjt2ht63daqcaj863,,sa94hkqj72dk743c2,|rh||AH|Marty Bergen Online Lesson|AH|2 Way Checkback|AH|Hand 26|MB|1sp1hp1np2dp|NT|^B@2
This is our first example for a 2@D rebid by responder. It is short and sweet. It turns out to be identical to the New Minor Forcing Auction. With his game forcing hand, responder bids 2@D over 1NT. |
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Opener gets to talk about his distribution. So he is going to bid 2@H to show 3 hearts.|MB|2hp|
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


NT|^B@2
It says nothing additional about the strength of his hand. He must not jump even with a maximum. He is not the boss. Responder is only interested in finding the best game and not interested in exploring for slam. He knows their side has a 5-3 heart fit.|
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


NT|^B@2
With his singleton he has no interest in 3NT. He bids 4@H ending the auction, just like those playing New Minor Forcing would do.|MB|4hppp|
PG| ***** 59 ***** |


NT||

%%%
qx|a,wide|ST||pn|Opener,,Responder.|MD|1sq87haj2dk63ck874,,sk32hkq953d875caq,|rh||AH|Marty Bergen Online Lesson|AH|2 Way Checkback|AH|Hand 27|MB|1cp1hp1np2dp2hp|NT|^B@2
The auction (Hand 27) starts in an identical fashion to Hand 26. With 5 hearts and a game forcing hand, responder starts with 2@D and opener shows 3-card support by bidding 2@H.|
PG| ***** 60 ***** |


NT|^B@2
This time responder is not so sure he wants to play in hearts with his flat hand. It is also relevant that his short suit is the one that opener bid. Opener would usually have at least a 4-card suit. Since we are in a game forcing auction there is no hurry. I would rebid 2NT, obviously forcing.|MB|2NP|
PG| ***** 61 ***** |


NT|^B@2
I am telling partner I have a balanced hand and am willing to play in NT if you prefer. Opener has a flat hand with nothing to ruff. So he is happy to play in 3NT.|MB|3nPPP|
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


NT|^B@2
He has honors in all 4 suits. He would like to have better spades, but he knows partner has some spades, likely 3 of them. 3NT looks like a better contract than 4@H. |
PG| ***** 63 ***** |


NT|^B@2
If everything is wrong you could go down in either contract. But it would take some very unlucky circumstances to defeat 3NT whereas taking 10 tricks in hearts is much harder. I think this is a very logical auction. Hope you agree.|
PG| ***** 64 ***** |


NT||
%%%
qx|a,wide|ST||pn|Opener,,Responder.|MD|1sq92ht63daqcaj863,,sa4hakq872dk642c2,|rh||AH|Marty Bergen Online Lesson|AH|2 Way Checkback|AH|Hand 31|MB|1cp1hp1np2dp2hp|NT|^B@2
In hand 31, Opener bids 2@H when the auction starts 1@C-1@H-1NT-2@D, to show 3-card support. |
PG| ***** 65 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Responder, is interested in slam. It wouldn't be wrong for him to bid 3@H. But responder has a singleton club. That is something he would like opener to know about. |
PG| ***** 66 ***** |


NT|^B@2
If opener has a lot of his values in clubs, such as the @CKQ or the @CKQJ, then he is not going to have enough outside of clubs for there to be a slam. So responder has an opportunity to make a splinter bid of 4@C, showing club shortness.|MB|4cp|
PG| ***** 67 ***** |


NT|^B@2
We call this a 'self-splinter' because the player is making the splinter with his suit as trump. Over 2@H, it is clear, when responder bids 4@C as a splinter bid, that hearts are trump. |
PG| ***** 68 ***** |


NT|^B@2
This auction isn't for everybody. If you want to bid 3@H instead of 4@C, that is fine with me. But playing with the right partner, I would bid 4@C. It is NOT Gerber.|
PG| ***** 69 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Opener thinks, 'Well, that's not bad. My ace-jack-fifth of clubs is a much better holding opposite a singleton than king-queen-fifth. I don't love my hand. But I do have a nice diamond holding with the @DA and @DQ. My partner could easily have the @DK. So I will control bid 4@D.|MB|4dp|
PG| ***** 70 ***** |


NT|^B@2
If all partner now does is bid 4@H over 4@D, I will call it a day.' 4@D is all responder needs to hear. He bids 4NT.|MB|4np|
PG| ***** 71 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Opener shows 2 key cards.|MB|5hp|
PG| ***** 72 ***** |


NT|^B@2
Responder knows they are 2 aces since he holds the @HK. Responder does not think they have 7 but he keeps the ball in play. If partner has the perfect hand they might have a grand slam. It would not be wrong to just
bid 6@H. But responder bids 5NT.|MB|5n|
PG| ***** 73 ***** |


NT|^B@2
And opener shows no kings.|MB|6cp|
PG| ***** 74 ***** |


NT|^B@2
So responder stops in 6@H. This looks like a very good slam to me. You might even make 7 on a good day if you can set up the 5th club. We had a logical auction to get to 6@H.|MB|6hppp|
PG| ***** 75 ***** |


